<br>
He is pushing for his new volutary emissions reduction program. The thing is though, back in 1992, President George Herbert Walker Bush signed an agreement from the Rio Earth Summit that called for voluntary greenhouse gas reductions. Yet emissions increased, and so a few years later civilized nations called for a firmer approach. That resulted in the 1997 Kyoto Protocol, which last year was embraced by over 160 nations -- excluding the world's biggest polluter, the United States. The younger Bush is merely re-packaging what failed in 1992. <br>
<br>
What's better he invented a new fuzzy math to prove this time that it will work. It says greenhouse gasses can increase at a portion of the economic growth. May sound good until you realize that energy useage increases at a much lower percentage than economic growth. <br>
<br>
Bush has his environmental plans written by industry for the love of god. What should we expect. It's like letting the guys with sports cars write the moving violations laws. <br>
<br>
Sagemon, I carpool to work. I make less than the average American, therefore the income tax is a relatively bigger burden on myself, so by transferring the payments to taxpayers it will increase the burden on the lower levels of the tax bracket while decreasing the burden on the factories, who may have no tax burden soon, according to Bush's plans. Is it easier to right and enforce tax breaks for enivironmentally friendly companies or for environmentally friendly individuals. Factories already get tax breaks for money they spend on safety measures, so all this plan does is let those who don't choose to spend on safety off the hook and which, in a competitive capitallistic society, will encourage companies to NOT take safety precautions as it will affect there bottom line. As we know the company who can produce the most goods at the lowest price is the one at the greatest advantage in our economic system. <br>
<br>
